8a3eb-1 | 2026-06-17T23:33:36Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 |  \n The single most important mechanism is the **settle window** — the propagation round-trip wait. Without it you cannot even approximate coordination, because you'd read claims before peers' claims have reached your relays. \n  \n ``` \n SETTLE = 1500ms          # ~ relay propagation RTT for your relay set \n TTL    = 120s            # lease length \n RENEW_BEFORE = 30s \n  \n acquire(resource): \n     rid   = normalize(resource)          # canonical abs path; dir claim covers descendants \n     mine  = build_claim(d=rid, scope, session, expiration=now+TTL) \n     publish(mine, relays=relevant_relays(resource)) \n  \n     sleep(SETTLE)                        # let peers' concurrent claims propagate to us \n  \n     claims = read_active_claims(rid)     # all 34110 with state=claimed, not expired, \n                                          # including shared-scope overlap on parent/child paths \n     conflicting = [c for c in claims if overlaps(c, mine) and c.pubkey != mine.pubkey] \n     if conflicting is empty: \n         return HELD                      # advisory hold \n     winner = min(conflicting + [mine], key=ordering) \n     if winner is mine: \n         return HELD \n     else: \n         publish(release(mine))           # yield gracefully \n         return WAIT(winner)              # observe winner's release/expiry, retry \n  \n ordering(claim): \n     # earliest intent wins; deterministic tie-break so all parties agree without communication \n     return (claim.created_at, claim.id_lexicographic)   # id, NOT pubkey-only: \n         # pubkey tie-break lets one operator always win; event-id is fairer & still deterministic \n  \n renew(): re-publish 34110 with new expiration before now > expiration - RENEW_BEFORE \n release(): publish 34110 with state=released \n ```
8a3eb-2 | 2026-06-17T23:33:36Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | **Overlap rule:** `overlaps()` is path-prefix aware. A claim on `/repo/src` conflicts with a claim on `/repo/src/foo.ts`. `scope:shared` (e.g., read-only/analysis) overlaps only with `exclusive`, not with other `shared`. \n 
8a3eb-3 | 2026-06-17T23:33:40Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 |  \n ## What your example actually means, abstracted up \n  \n Your dev-fleet framing from earlier was too small. The todo-app / podcast-app example reveals the real shape, and it's a bigger and better idea. \n  \n **1. Every app becomes a citizen, not a destination.** A todo app used to be a place you *go*. In your setup it's an *agent with a role* in a society — "organizer of the human's attention." The podcast app isn't a place you browse; it's a *capability* — "turn my interests into audio" — that other agents can invoke and that can generate on demand. Apps stop competing for screen time and start contributing functions to a mesh. \n  \n **2. You are the integration layer being dissolved.** This is the core of it. Today the human is the message bus between siloed apps: you hear a product idea and *you* hand-carry it into your todo list; you get curious and *you* go hunt a podcast. You are the glue — a slow, lossy, manual courier between islands. What you've built is the agents taking that courier job away from you. The coding-agent-raises-a-hand-to-the-todo-agent path means *you are no longer the API between your own tools.* That's the whole game. Not "agents coordinate on a repo" — "the human stops being middleware." \n  \n **3. The human inverts from operator to node.** "Raise a hand to my todo agent and I'll have it organized in my day and get back to the agents." You've scheduled *yourself into the workflow* as a high-authority, high-latency oracle the agents consult. You're not the conductor anymore; you're a privileged participant in a mesh — the one with veto and priority, but still one node among many. \n  \n **4. Roles and division of labor emerge with no central orchestrator.** The todo agent organizes, the podcast agent synthesizes, the coding agents build. Nobody assigned these. The agents *know each other's roles* and route work accordingly. That's an organization self-assembling — a society of specialists — which is a categorically different thing from TENEX's *deliberately* orchestrated fleet. TENEX is a hierarchy with a runtime. This is an *economy* with a protocol. \n  \n **5. Cross-person stops being the scary edge and becomes continuous.** Your todo agent ↔ your wife's todo agent for shared tasks isn't a dangerous feature you bolt on — in this framing it's the *obvious* next hop. Household, team, friends are just more nodes. The "social network of agents" grows bottom-up from shared tasks and shared interests, not as a risky product phase. (The security problem is still real — but the *unit* is "trusted circle mesh," which is a saner starting frame than "open network of strangers' agents.") \n  \n **6. Push replaces pull; the system becomes anticipatory.** "Trending toward pushing information from complex, different systems." Today you pull — open the app, run the query. Here, agents push what's relevant based on a live model of your goals and interests. Ambient, not on-demand. \n  \n So the abstraction is: **the operating system is being turned inside out.** Apps were islands you multitasked between, with the human as the integration runtime. Now there's an agent-level fabric where apps are services in a society and the integration runtime is a mesh of agents speaking a common protocol — Unix pipes, but for intelligent agents over a cryptographic social graph, with the human as a privileged participant rather than the shell. \n  \n And that reframes the project cleanly: **tenex-edge is the citizenship protocol for an agent society that spans every app in your life — not a coordination tool for your dev fleet.** The dev-collision stuff (which the red-team already shredded) is one narrow, weak slice of a much larger thing: dissolving the human-as-glue across *all* your software. \n 
