8a3eb-11 | 2026-06-17T23:33:53Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | `pc` is invoked **per-hook, short-lived, stateless-per-call**, talking to local SQLite. That model is fine for memory injection. It is **fatal for tenex-edge**, because: \n  \n - A Nostr relay connection is a persistent WebSocket. You cannot open/close it on every `PreToolUse` — handshake + REQ + EOSE latency would be 100s of ms on the agent's hot path. \n - Presence/heartbeat (property #3) requires a process that is *alive between hook calls* to emit liveness and decay peers to idle. \n - Advisory-lock queries (property #6) must answer in single-digit ms from hot in-memory state, not a cold relay round-trip. \n  \n Therefore the architecture is a hard split that `pc` does not have: \n  \n > **Thin, stateless hook shims (the `pc` invocation model) → Unix-domain socket → one long-running per-device daemon (`tenex-edged`) that owns the persistent relay connection, the live subscription/replica, the lock table, and presence state.** \n  \n That split *is* the component diagram. The shims keep `pc`'s "fast, fire-and-forget, exit-0-always" discipline; the daemon adds the hot state `pc` never needed. \n 
