8a3eb-13 | 2026-06-17T23:33:59Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 |  \n Two things rise above the rest as *durable* — they survive even if a host vendor ships native coordination tomorrow and eats your locking feature: \n  \n - **Vendor-independent agent identity.** An agent's reputation, memory, and relationships outliving any single session, host, or vendor. You don't own that today and nobody's building it for *heterogeneous* hosts. This is the milkshake; the plugin is just the straw. \n - **Provenance.** Every piece of work cryptographically signed with *which agent, under which human's key, in which host* produced it. Six months from now, "why is this code like this?" becomes answerable. As agents write more of everything, attestation stops being nice-to-have. \n  \n Both flow from identity, not from coordination. That's the tell for where the center of gravity should be. \n 
8a3eb-14 | 2026-06-17T23:34:02Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 |  \n ### 3. Nostr / TENEX-Compatible Communication \n  \n This is **decoupled from the LLM agent loop** — the Rust agent does not autonomously consume or respond to inbound Nostr events. The agent handler explicitly states (agent_note_handler.rs:15): *"No LLM responder loop. Still on the Swift `NostrAgentResponder` path."* — the autonomous agent-driven inbound-note loop is not wired in Rust. \n  \n However, the **transport and event primitives for agent-to-agent Nostr communication are fully present:** \n  \n #### Inbound Agent Notes (Subscribe) \n  \n **File:** `/Users/pablofernandez/Work/podcast-player/apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/agent_note_handler.rs` \n  \n - **Kind:** `kind:1` (NIP-01 text note) \n - **Filter:** Subscribed via NMP relay pool with: \n   - `kinds: [1]` \n   - `#p` tag ref to own pubkey (inbox filter, NIP-10 recipient tag) \n   - `InterestScope::Global` + `InterestLifecycle::OneShot` \n - **Tag structure for replies (built by `build_agent_note_tags`):** \n   - `["a", <NIP-72-coordinate>]` — optional NIP-72 channel anchor (0+ per call) \n   - `["e", <root-event-id>, "", "root"]` — NIP-10 root marker (if replying to a thread) \n   - `["e", <inbound-event-id>, "", "reply"]` — NIP-10 reply marker (if different from root) \n   - `["p", <recipient-pubkey>]` — recipient pubkey \n - **Observer:** `AgentNotesObserver` receives events from NMP, filters self-authored, projects to `AgentNoteSummary` (truncates to 200 max inbound notes). \n - **Trust:** All inbound notes projected with `trusted: false` (trust gate not yet implemented). \n  \n #### Outbound Agent Notes (Publish) [...]    - Tags: `["a", coord]` (NIP-72), `["e", id, "", "root"/"reply"]` (NIP-10), `["p", pubkey]` (recipient), `["t", category]` (topic), `["-"]` (NIP-70 protected) \n  \n 5. **Decoupling LLM from Nostr:** The agent loop (`agent_llm`) is **entirely independent** of the Nostr layer. It queries the local store, calls tools, and returns prose. Inbound Nostr notes are projected into the UI/store by observers but do **not** auto-trigger LLM responses. This boundary is deliberate — the Rust code provides transport; Swift drives higher-level routing (the `NostrAgentResponder` path handles autonomous replies). \n 
8a3eb-15 | 2026-06-17T23:34:04Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | `(a)` Claude Code = premium tier: hooks give lifecycle + **blocking**. `(b)` Codex/Cursor = MCP tier: observe via tool calls, inject via tool results, **cannot block the host's own edits**. `(c)` OpenCode = JS plugin tier (it ships an SDK; `~/.config/opencode` has a node plugin layout). \n  \n --- \n  \n ## 3. Per-host integration table \n  \n The discriminating axis, per the advisor, is **can-block?** — whether the host can be made to *wait* (deny a tool call), versus only receive ambient context. Only this separates real coordination (#6) from awareness (#3). \n  \n | Host | Observe via | Inject context via | **Can block / "wait"?** | Session-binding handle | Transport to daemon | \n |---|---|---|---|---|---| \n | **Claude Code** | `PreToolUse`/`PostToolUse`/`SessionStart`/`Stop`/`SessionEnd`/`UserPromptSubmit` hooks; stdin JSON gives `session_id`, `cwd`, `prompt`, `transcript_path`, `tool_input`, `workspace.current_dir`, `context_window` (all verified live) | `UserPromptSubmit`/`PostToolUse` `additionalContext`; `<system-reminder>` text; statusLine; MCP tool results | **YES** — `PreToolUse` with `permissionDecision: "deny"` (or exit 2). *Note: my live config does not use PreToolUse — this is a capability tenex-edge adds, not one already wired.* | `session_id` from hook stdin (resumable/unstable — see §6) | hook shim → UDS; plus stdio MCP | \n | **Codex** | MCP tool calls only (`~/.codex/config.toml` `[mcp_servers]` confirmed). No process hooks. | MCP tool results; system-prompt preamble | **NO** (advisory only — agent must voluntarily call a `check_lock` tool; degrade to warn-after-the-fact) | MCP session lifetime + cwd | stdio MCP server | \n | **OpenCode** | JS plugin/SDK callbacks (tool events, session events) | plugin-injected messages; MCP | **PARTIAL** — depends on plugin API surface for veto; assume advisory until verified | plugin session id | plugin → UDS / MCP | \n | **Cursor** | MCP only (`mcp.json`) | MCP tool results | **NO** | MCP session + workspace | stdio MCP server | \n | **Mobile / embedded agent** | in-app SDK calls into a thin client lib | rendered in-app; SDK callback | depends on app; advisory by default | app-assigned session id | localhost HTTP / direct nostr-sdk if no daemon | \n  \n **The portability principle:** MCP is the lowest-common-denominator substrate every host above speaks; Claude Code hooks are the premium tier adding **blocking + lifecycle**. Where a host has no hook, tenex-edge **degrades gracefully to MCP-server-as-observer**: it still gets presence and *advisory* locks (the agent calls `edge.claim_path` / `edge.check_path` as tools), it just loses the hard "wait" and the automatic session start/stop signals (those become tool-call-inferred). \n 
