8a3eb-17 | 2026-06-17T23:34:08Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | ## 1. Identity model: three layers \n  \n Don't conflate "who an agent is," "what session it's running," and "is it alive right now." These have totally different change rates and therefore different event ranges. \n  \n | Layer | Change rate | Event range | Why | \n |---|---|---|---| \n | **Agent identity** | rarely (per keypair) | `kind:0` (metadata) + roster attestation `34199` | durable, signed once | \n | **Session record** | per session, mutable | param-replaceable `34100` (`d`=session-id) | one operator runs *many* concurrent sessions → must be `d`-keyed, a plain replaceable (one-per-pubkey) can't represent N sessions | \n | **Heartbeat** | every ~30s | ephemeral `24100` | high-frequency liveness, no relay storage cost | \n  \n The load-bearing call is the session record being **parameterized-replaceable, not plain replaceable**. An operator with Claude Code on a laptop and Codex on a desktop and an embedded agent on a phone has three live sessions under potentially the same or different agent keys; `d`-tag = session-id is the only range that models that. \n  \n The consequence I'll state plainly: **session *start* must be the durable PR event (`34100`), never the ephemeral heartbeat.** A late-joining observer (your phone opening the dashboard) sees nothing of an ephemeral heartbeat until the next ping fires; it needs the stored session record to know the session exists at all. Heartbeat only refreshes liveness. \n 
8a3eb-18 | 2026-06-17T23:34:08Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 |  \n The consequence I'll state plainly: **session *start* must be the durable PR event (`34100`), never the ephemeral heartbeat.** A late-joining observer (your phone opening the dashboard) sees nothing of an ephemeral heartbeat until the next ping fires; it needs the stored session record to know the session exists at all. Heartbeat only refreshes liveness. \n  [...]  \n **Stop semantics:** session stop is a **state-write** (`34100` with `status:stopped`), *not* a NIP-09 deletion. Deletion is unreliable on a gossip bus; a final stored state transition is observable and durable. Same for lock release (`34110` `state:released`). \n  \n **Stale presence:** liveness is **computed client-side** from heartbeat `created_at` + a staleness window (e.g. alive if last `24100` < 90s old, given 30s ping interval). NIP-40 `expiration` is published as a *courtesy hint* to relays that honor it — never relied upon. A session whose process is SIGKILL'd writes no stop event; observers age it out by missing heartbeats and may optionally write a `34100` `status:stopped` tombstone on the dead session's behalf is *not* allowed (wrong signer) — instead the dashboard shows it "stale" and the operator's own coordinator key may publish a `34110` release for the dead session's locks (see §3 reaping). [...]  \n **Stale presence:** liveness is **computed client-side** from heartbeat `created_at` + a staleness window (e.g. alive if last `24100` < 90s old, given 30s ping interval). NIP-40 `expiration` is published as a *courtesy hint* to relays that honor it — never relied upon. A session whose process is SIGKILL'd writes no stop event; observers age it out by missing heartbeats and may optionally write a `34100` `status:stopped` tombstone on the dead session's behalf is *not* allowed (wrong signer) — instead the dashboard shows it "stale" and the operator's own coordinator key may publish a `34110` release for the dead session's locks (see §3 reaping). \n  [...] **Three key tiers:** \n  \n 1. **Person root key** (one per operator). Lives in the OS keychain (macOS Keychain / `secret-service`), or via a bunker (`bunker://`, already supported in the TENEX TUI). Signs the *roster*: a NIP-51 list event ("these are my agents / my devices"). This is the trust anchor for property #2 and #5. \n 2. **Per-agent durable keypair** (one per logical agent identity, e.g. "pablo's claude-code", "pablo's codex"). Stored in the daemon's vault. This carries reputation/history. Listed in the roster. No delegation event needed — authorization is "is this pubkey in a roster the root key signed?", checkable by anyone. \n 3. **Session = first-class ephemeral object, not a key.** A session is a *status event* (kind modeled on TENEX's kind:24010 project-status) signed by the per-agent key, tagged to: the agent pubkey, the project NIP-33 coordinate (`a` tag), the host kind (`claude-code`/`codex`/…), `cwd`, and a state field `start|active|idle|stop`. Heartbeated (replaceable kind keyed by session id). Idle decay handled by the daemon. This mirrors exactly what `awareness.rs` does locally with its one-line intent, promoted to a signed, relayed event. \n  \n **Why no per-session keys:** sessions are too churny (resume, crash, reopen) to deserve durable identity; binding them to the durable agent key preserves continuity while letting sessions be cheap and ephemeral. \n  \n ---
8a3eb-19 | 2026-06-17T23:34:10Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | ## 4. The thinnest "I'd use this daily" slice (MVP) \n  \n **MVP = S1 (advisory lock) + S2 (shared-bug dedup), solo, across Claude Code and Codex on one machine.** Strictly single-player. No cross-person, not even read-only. \n  \n Concretely, the whole MVP is: \n - A hook in each host that, on file-open/edit, emits a signed Nostr event `{agent, session, repo, path, goal, status, ts}` and subscribes to the same. \n - An advisory-lock check before writing a file another agent holds — surfaced as a message in the agent's own transcript, with hold/work-around/override. \n - A stack-signature match so "you both hit this error" fires. \n  \n **Why exactly these two:** \n - **S1 alone is the "I'd never turn it off" moment.** Anyone running two agents has eaten a self-inflicted conflict. Eliminating that is a daily, felt win from the first hour — that's the bar for "I'd use this daily," and S1 clears it solo. \n - **S2 is what elevates it from a mutex to a *superpower*.** Lock-only is defensive ("don't break things"); dedup is offensive ("get more done"). Together they tell the whole story the product is about: agents that coordinate instead of collide. \n - **Both run on one machine with one key** — no trust model, no second human, no server. The hardest parts of the vision (cross-person trust) are deferred entirely. You ship the spine and nothing else. \n  \n **Deliberate MVP decision (per the open question):** *solo-only, no cross-person read.* The "daily use" claim is strongest when it's true for a user with zero collaborators. Adding even read-only cross-person dilutes the install story ("who do I follow?") and weakens the single-player promise. Cross-person is the v1 wedge, not MVP seasoning. \n 
