8a3eb-22 | 2026-06-17T23:34:15Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 |  \n **v1 — "My work follows me, and my collaborator's agent is visible."** \n Add durable identity across devices (S3 handoff), the awareness feed + self-writing standup (S4, S8), and the *first cross-person rung*: one-time key exchange → read-only shared work feed (S5). Lock-as-negotiation (S7) lands here too. Now it's multi-device and lightly multi-person, but trust is still low-stakes (read-only). \n  \n **Ambitious — "My agents and my friends' agents are one coordinated mesh."** \n Full cross-person Q&A with consent policies (S6 — "ask Calle's agent"), and cryptographic provenance/attestation on every commit across all hosts (S9). The endgame: a decentralized, signed coordination fabric where any agent in any host can safely discover, query, and collaborate with any other under explicit human-key consent. This is the inverse-TENEX vision fully realized — TENEX hosts the agents; tenex-edge makes *everyone's* agents interoperable. [...] ## The deepest tension: there are actually two products here \n  \n This is the thing to be most clear-eyed about. "My agent asks Calle's agent a question" is the magic moment everyone wants — and it's a **categorically different product** from everything else: \n  \n 1. **A nervous system for *my* fleet.** Single-player. My keys, my machines, my agents. Safe. Valuable immediately. No network effect to bootstrap. \n 2. **A social network for *everyone's* agents.** Cross-person. The instant you cross that boundary, you are piping a foreign, autonomous LLM's output *into your own agent's head*. That's not "feature #5 with a security note" — it's a fundamentally different risk surface (prompt injection, exfiltration, your roadmap leaking over a relay) and a fundamentally different adoption model (network-effect-gated, needs a trust model that doesn't exist yet). \n  \n Cross-person is the north star that earns the tweets and the funding. But it is the *destination*, and pretending it's adjacent to the single-player product is how you'd accidentally ship the dangerous thing first. Build the customs office before you open the borders. \n 
