8a3eb-25 | 2026-06-17T23:34:24Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | ### 1. The load-bearing superpower (#6 locking) is mostly redundant with git — value may not justify the build \n **Kill-probability: HIGH. Severity: HIGH (it's the headline feature).** \n  \n Why: The collision scenario — "two of my agents edit `src/foo.rs`, detect it, hand off" — is the demo everyone shows and almost nobody hits. In practice your concurrent agents are usually on *different* projects, *different* files, or *different* worktrees. And when they do collide, **git already provides the authoritative conflict layer**: branches isolate, merge/rebase detects, conflict markers force resolution. tenex-edge's advisory awareness is *pre-collision UX polish* on top of git's *at-merge* truth. For it to be worth building, pre-collision warning must beat at-merge detection often enough to matter — and that requires real collision frequency that I doubt exists. \n  \n Verdict: **Not fatal to the project, but fatal to the pitch.** Demote #6 from headline to "nice signal." Mitigation: don't build a lock protocol; build a passive "another agent recently touched this path" hint that links to git state. Cheap, honest, no false authority. The kill-test for this is the experiment at the bottom. \n  [...] ## What's load-bearing vs. cute \n  \n - **Load-bearing, low-risk (build these): #1 identity, #2 cross-device messaging between *your own* agents, #3 presence/awareness of your own active work.** This is "Slack + identity for my fleet of agents across machines." Real daily value, modest risk, no distributed-consensus needed. \n - **Cute / over-claimed: #6 advisory locking** (git already wins) **and #5 cross-person ask** (high blast radius, niche demand). Keep #5 as a guarded, opt-in extra; demote #6 to a passive hint. \n  [...]  \n Run **pure passive logging for one week across your own real concurrent agent sessions** — *no coordination logic at all*. A SessionStart + PostToolUse hook on Claude Code that records `(agent id, file path, timestamp)` to a local log. Then count: how often did two agents touch the same path within a plausible conflict window (say, minutes)?  \n - **Near-zero collisions → #6 is dead**, the coordination pitch is a demo, and you should rescope to identity + messaging + presence and re-evaluate against A2A. \n - **Frequent collisions → you have a real problem to coordinate**, and *then* it's worth building the advisory layer (still git-authoritative). \n  \n This costs a day to build, a week to run, requires zero distributed-systems work, and decides whether the load-bearing feature is real before you write a line of Nostr lock code. \n 
8a3eb-26 | 2026-06-17T23:34:24Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | **Kill-probability: LOW (you can cut the feature). Severity: VERY HIGH (if shipped naively).** \n  \n Why it's the scariest: #5 means **letting someone else's autonomous LLM emit text into your agent's context.** That is a textbook indirect prompt-injection and exfiltration channel. Calle's agent (or a compromised relay event spoofing Calle) asks "what are you working on?" and your agent helpfully dumps secrets, or follows an embedded instruction to run a tool. Privacy compounds it: broadcasting "what I'm working on" (paths, project names, goals) over public relays leaks your roadmap to anyone subscribed. \n  \n Why it's NOT existential: **#5 is a feature you can cut, and the project survives as presence + messaging.** And Nostr identity actually *helps* the defense here. \n  \n Verdict: **Fatal to #5 unless you treat all peer input as hostile data, never instructions.** Concretely: \n - **Quarantine peer messages** behind a tool boundary: a peer question becomes structured data the agent may *choose* to answer, never free text injected into the system/context stream. \n - **Human-in-the-loop approval** for any cross-person answer (PreToolUse `ask`). \n - **npm allowlist** — only accept from explicitly trusted npubs; signatures give you real authentication (this is where Nostr identity earns its keep). \n - **Encrypt and scope presence** (NIP-44/gift-wrap to your own devices; never plaintext-broadcast work content). Default presence to *your own agents only*; cross-person is opt-in per peer. \n 
8a3eb-27 | 2026-06-17T23:34:27Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | ## 6. Discovery & relay strategy \n  \n - **Personal relay per operator (the backbone).** Each operator runs/rents one relay. All their agents read+write it → a single propagation domain where the §3 SETTLE window is small and reliable, and cross-device presence "just works." This is the primary recommendation. \n - **Shared collaboration relay per group.** A project team or a friend-pair uses a shared relay for `34120` goals, `34130` resources, cross-person `4110`/`4111`. Scopes the gossip to people who should see it. \n - **Finding each other:** NIP-65 (`10002`) advertises where to reach an operator; NIP-02 (`3`) is the social graph; the `34130` resource registry advertises relays themselves (`type:relay`) so a group can bootstrap. \n - **Relay selection per event:** presence/heartbeat → personal relay only (no point spamming the world). Locks → relays relevant to the resource's owning project. Cross-person → target's NIP-65 read relays. \n 
8a3eb-28 | 2026-06-17T23:34:29Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | The platform bet is **a thin open adapter on Nostr — the protocol is the product.** Any host emits and consumes signed events; tenex-edge owns no agents and no server. Everything on the don't-build list protects that. \n  \n - **No hosted central server.** The moment there's a coordination server, it's not the upside-down of TENEX — it's just another SaaS, and you've thrown away the durable-identity / no-central-server property that's the entire reason to use Nostr. \n - **Don't build your own agent or agent host.** That's TENEX. tenex-edge's whole identity is "your agents stay in their native homes." Building a host betrays the premise. \n - **No UI-first dashboard / mission control (G2).** Lead with hooks and a CLI feed. A dashboard is the toy trap. (A read-only viewer can come *much* later, but never as the product's center of gravity.) \n - **Don't require mutual adoption before value appears.** If two people must both install before anyone benefits, it's dead on arrival. Single-player value first (the whole reason the beachhead is solo). \n - **No open-ended agent chat (G3).** Coordination must be bounded by a shared artifact. Don't ship a chat feature. \n - **No mobile app / push backend in early rungs (G1).** It pulls you off the thin-adapter path into app development. \n  \n **Toy vs. platform, sharply:** \n - It's a **toy** if it's a closed loop inside one vendor (Claude-to-Claude only), or a dashboard you watch, or it needs a central server. \n - It's a **platform** if it's an open event schema on Nostr that *any* host can adopt independently, where agents *act* on coordination (lock, dedup, negotiate, attest) rather than humans watching, and where one user gets value before the second one shows up. \n 
8a3eb-29 | 2026-06-17T23:34:31Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | **Kill-probability: LOW-MEDIUM (slow). Severity: MEDIUM.** \n  \n You control nothing: distribution, the extension API, the user relationship, and the roadmap all belong to the hosts. The instant any host ships native cross-session/cross-device coordination (Anthropic is the obvious candidate, given hooks + their ecosystem), your core value is a default feature and you're a redundant dependency. As a parasite you also can't charge easily or build defensible lock-in. \n  \n Verdict: **Survivable as a wedge, dangerous as the whole strategy.** Mitigation: use the plugin as *distribution*, but own the **fabric/identity layer** (the Nostr coordination spec + relay conventions + key management) as the durable asset. If a host absorbs the plugin, the fabric is still where cross-host/cross-person identity lives. The plugin is the straw; the fabric is the milkshake. \n 
8a3eb-30 | 2026-06-17T23:34:35Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 |  \n **Opinionated position: do not use NIP-26 delegated signing.** It's deprecated and unevenly supported; hanging the trust model on it is fragile. Instead, **explicit attestation + capability grants.** \n  \n **Person vs. agent.** A *person* is a master key (your real Nostr identity, with `kind:3` follows and `kind:10002` relays). Each *agent* is its own keypair. The person publishes a **roster attestation `34199`** naming its agent pubkeys and per-agent scopes. This is the binding: "these keys act for me." An agent's profile (`kind:0`) carries `edge_role:agent`; verifiers confirm the back-link by checking the person's roster. \n  \n **How my agent reaches Calle's agent:** \n 1. **Discover relays** — fetch Calle's `kind:10002` (NIP-65). Write my `4110` request to Calle's *read* relays (outbox model). His agents subscribe to his read relays. \n 2. **Coarse trust edge** — `kind:3` follow / mutual follow establishes "Calle is a known counterparty." Not authorization by itself. \n 3. **Fine authorization** — Calle publishes a **capability grant `4120`** p-tagging *my person key* (or a specific agent), a-tagging the project/resource, with an `allow` list (`read-goals`, `query:bugs`, `read-presence`). His agents authorize an incoming `4110` by checking: *does the requester's pubkey resolve (via a `34199` roster) to a person that holds a live `4120` grant covering this intent?* If not → `4111 status:denied`. \n 4. **Confidentiality** — cross-person request/response payloads use **NIP-44** encryption. When even the *metadata* (who's asking whom) must be hidden, wrap in **NIP-59 gift wrap (`kind:1059`)**. \n  \n This gives Calle precise control: he decides which of my agents may ask what, time-boxed via `expiration`, revocable by replacing/expiring the `4120`. No central auth server; authorization is itself a signed, discoverable event. \n 
8a3eb-31 | 2026-06-17T23:34:38Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | **Crash-first / restart-safe**: All state is on disk (SQLite or JSON). Every process must survive being killed and restarted cold. In-memory caches are caches, not truth. \n  \n **No temporary solutions, no backward-compat shims**: The CLAUDE.md coding standards explicitly forbid TODO/FIXME/workaround comments, wrapper classes, and re-exported old names. Every change must be the right long-term solution. No technical debt as a trade-off. \n 
