f3a73-2 | 2026-06-17T23:37:02Z | session:f3a730bf-9a3b-4952-b687-c93ade5fd7ec | Assistant: Right — that's a real bug. Mentions are stored `kind:1` events that persist on the relay, and `inbox`'s dedup is **per-session** (keyed by target_session). A new session re-fetches the same stored mention and, because its session id is new, re-delivers it. The fix: dedup delivery **per-agent** — once an agent has seen a mention in any session, never re-deliver it. Let me add a `seen_mentions` table. \n  \n Assistant: Now wire it: skip already-seen in the engine's `route_mention` and in `inbox`'s self-fetch, and mark seen after `inbox` drains. \n  \n Assistant: Now build, reinstall, and verify the drain across sessions (a mention seen in session 1 must NOT reappear in a fresh session 2). \n  \n Assistant: **Fixed and verified:** session 1 saw `drain-test-msg` once; a fresh session 2 of the same agent shows an **empty** inbox. Let me update the memory note that flagged this as a known issue. \n  \n Assistant: Fixed. You're right — mentions weren't being drained across sessions. \n  \n **The cause:** a mention is a stored `kind:1` event that persists on the relay forever. `inbox`'s dedup was **per-session** (keyed by `target_session`), so when you stopped and started a new session, its self-fetch re-pulled the same stored mention and — because the session id was new — delivered it again. \n  \n **The fix:** dedup is now **per-agent**. A `seen_mentions(agent_pubkey, event_id)` record is written when `inbox` delivers a mention, and both the `inbox` self-fetch and the engine's routing skip any mention id that agent has already seen. So once the agent reads a message in *any* session, it never resurfaces. \n  \n Verified on a clean relay: \n ``` \n session 1 inbox → [mention from bob@projB] drain-test-msg     (delivered once, marked seen) \n session 2 inbox → []                                          (new session, not re-delivered) \n ``` \n  \n 37 tests pass; binary rebuilt, reins