f3a73-26 | 2026-06-17T23:37:45Z | session:f3a730bf-9a3b-4952-b687-c93ade5fd7ec |  \n Here's how I'd get started. \n  \n ## The absolute MVP: Rung 0, pure \n  \n Identity + local awareness on one device. Nothing else. \n  \n - An agent that is a **stable citizen across sessions** on one machine — it remembers who it is, its role, what it's been doing. \n - Agents that can **see what the other agents are doing** — the local standup board. \n - **Zero network, zero trust model, zero consensus.** \n  \n This is not greenfield. `proactive-context` already runs the awareness board (Rust + SQLite, hooked into Claude Code). The *entire* MVP delta is: **give the agents on that board a durable identity.** That's the thinnest cut that proves the two primitives the whole project rests on — identity and awareness — are the right primitives, before any distributed complexity exists to muddy the signal. \n  \n I'd resist the temptation to make the MVP "dramatic." The spec's Q3 worries that identity+awareness alone is *undramatic*, and it's right — the emotionally alive moment is an agent **routing work** to another agent or raising a hand to you. But that's the **very next increment**, not the MVP. Ship the floor first; the routing moment is the cheapest "wow" and it's load-bearing, so it earns its own deliberate step rather than being smuggled into v0. \n  \n ## How to get started — two things in parallel, day one \n  \n 1. **Extend `pc`, don't rebuild.** It already has the awareness board and the Claude Code hooks. Bolt durable identity onto it. \n 2. **Start the Q1 collision clock immediately.** Q1 — "do costly collisions between concurrent agents actually happen?" — decides whether the entire coordination *ceiling* (Rung 2 locks) is a pillar or a demo. The test is pure passive logging: record `(agent, path, timestamp)`, no coordination logic, ~a day to build. If you fold it into Rung 0 on day one, you'll have a week of real data sitting there by the time Rung 2 scope is even a question. That's the single highest-leverage near-free move available to you. \n  \n So: Rung 0 = identity + awareness + a passive collision logger that does nothing but watch. \n  \n ## How to organize code for the larger vision \n  \n Three seams. Each one exists to protect a specific principle from the spec, and getting them right is what lets Rung 0→1→2 be *swaps and additions* rather than rewrites. \n  \n **Seam 1 — Identity, decoupled from host *and* from `pc`.** \n Principle: "the host is a body; the identity is the person." Identity is the asset — the milkshake. So it must not be coupled to any host session, and it must not be coupled to `pc`'s local-awareness concern either. Concretely: I'd make `pc` the **first awareness-adapter feeding an identity-owning core**, rather than burying identity inside `pc`. Identity (the sovereign keypair, durable per-agent, anchored to a person) is the thing every later layer — presence, roles, reputation, provenance — hangs off of. It deserves to be the center, not a field in the awareness table. [...] Assistant: That's a real regression from adding `rig-core`: it pulled a second rustls crypto provider, so rustls 0.23 now sees both `ring` and `aws-lc-rs` and refuses to auto-pick one → panic the moment `inbox` opens a TLS connection to the relay. The fix is to install a default `CryptoProvider` at process startup. Let me see which providers are actually in the tree. \n  \n Assistant: Both `ring` and `aws-lc-rs` are in the tree (rig's `reqwest` enables both paths), so rustls can't pick a default. I'll install the `ring` provider at startup. Let me check `main.rs` then wire it. \n  \n Assistant: `doctor` (the TLS path that panicked) now works — publish OK + read-back. Let me confirm `tenex-edge inbox` itself and that tests still pass. \n  \n Assistant: Fixed — `tenex-edge inbox` runs cleanly now (rc=0, no panic), `doctor`'s TLS works, 45 lib + 1 e2e tests green, binary reinstalled+signed. \n  \n **Root cause:** adding `rig-core` brought its `reqwest`, which pulled a *second* rustls crypto provider (`aws-lc-rs`) alongside nostr-sdk's (`ring`). With both compiled in, rustls 0.23 can't auto-pick a default `CryptoProvider`, so it panics the instant any TLS handshake happens — which is exactly when `inbox` (and any relay-touching command) opens the `wss://` connection. `doctor`/`inbox` were the first to hit it because they open a fresh TLS connection. \n  \n **Fix:** install an explicit provider once at process startup, in `main()`: \n ```rust \n let _ = rustls::crypto::ring::default_provider().install_default(); \n ``` \n (plus `rustls = { version = "0.23", features = ["ring"] }` in Cargo.toml). Now every TLS connection — the inbox self-fetch, the engine, the rig distiller's HTTPS to OpenRouter — uses `ring` consistently. \n  \n Assistant: Recorded the gotcha in memory so it doesn't bite again. You're good to run `tenex-edge inbox` (and everything else) now — start a fresh session to pick up the rebuilt binary.
