162f9-8 | 2026-06-17T23:47:53Z | session:162f9965-82ca-420b-aa24-99faa15cb59a | **Bug A — same-pubkey sibling-session mentions dropped.** \n - **Root cause (the task's stated diagnosis was wrong — verified empirically):** there is NO local-delivery-on-publish and NO author self-skip in the code. `rpc_send_message` (`src/daemon/server.rs`) only called `transport.publish_signed` and relied entirely on the relay echoing the self-published event back to `handle_incoming`. Relays generally do NOT re-deliver an event to the connection that published it, so a same-machine A→B sibling mention was never routed at publish time. (The original repro also used a *dead* target session `555de1db`, alive=0 → `compute_targets` returned `[]`; that's a separate confound, not the same-pubkey bug.) \n - **Fix:** added synchronous local delivery in `rpc_send_message`: when `to_pubkey ∈ hosted_pubkeys()`, route the just-published event into the recipient session's inbox via the new `route_mention_into_with_id(store, to, mention, &event_id.to_hex())` (`src/runtime.rs`), using the SAME `EventId` returned by `publish_signed`. `enqueue_mention` is `INSERT OR IGNORE` on the inbox PK `(mention_event_id, target_session)`, so a later relay echo cannot double-deliver. `compute_targets(Some(B),[A,B])=[B]` naturally excludes the authoring session A. \n  \n **Bug B — per-agent dedup defeats session targeting.** \n - **Root cause:** `route_mention_into` (`src/runtime.rs:~231`) gated ALL mentions on `is_mention_seen(agent_pubkey, eid)` (`src/state.rs:737`), which is keyed on pubkey only. Once any sibling marked an event seen, the intended target session was blocked. (Note: this was NOT the cause of the *observed* live drop — the live repro showed no `seen_mentions` row at all — it's a real latent defect that the docs already claimed was fixed.) \n - **Fix (bypass, not schema migration — chosen to avoid colliding with the concurrent NIP-29 rewrite of `state.rs`):** the per-agent `is_mention_seen` check is now gated on `m.target_session.is_none()`. Agent-wide (untargeted) mentions still dedup per-agent (preserving "don't resurface in every session"); session-targeted mentions bypass it and rely on the per-(pubkey,session) idempotency of the inbox PK. Verified delivered inbox rows are never DELETEd (only `delivered=1`), so the PK reliably carries dedup. \n  \n **Bug C — sender identity resolution agent-agnostic.** \n - **Root cause:** `resolve_session` (`src/daemon/server.rs:317`) fell back to `latest_alive_session_for_project(project)` (`src/state.rs`), ignoring the invoking agent — so a `claude` send was signed/recorded as `opencode` when opencode was the latest-active session. \n - **Fix:** added `agent: Option<&str>` to `resolve_session`; added `Store::latest_alive_session_for_agent_in_project(agent, project)`; threaded `TENEX_EDGE_AGENT` through the CLI into the RPC params for `send_message`, `inbox`, `turn_check`, `wait_for_mention`, `user_prompt` (`src/cli.rs`). Explicit `--session` > `$TENEX_EDGE_SESSION` > agent-scoped-latest, with agent-agnostic fallback only when no agent is supplied. \n 
