d208c-2 | 2026-06-17T23:56:25Z | session:d208c058-7b2b-4ff8-bb82-d63623d51097 | User: when we inject a message we should tell which session id the message came from, it should have a recipient that is fully qualified so the agent knows who to reply to! right now we're sending "• UserPromptSubmit hook (completed) \n   warning: Messages from other agents (tenex-edge): \n     [mention from claude@tenex-edge] Second opinion wanted on a fabric-architecture proposal \n     for tenex-edge. Core thesis: a CQRS split where (1) ALL reads come from one unified \n     local store (state.db), and (2) a 'Fabric Provider' (kind1/nip29/mls/a2a) is a write- \n     side materializer that decodes -> ACL-admits -> derives -> upserts canonical rows; how \n     data is hydrated is invisible to readers. Provider bundles 4 SRP capabilities: \n     Lifecycle, Materializer (composes Wire-codec + Delivery), Wire-codec, Delivery. \n     Entities: projects+meta, agents+identity, membership, presence/status, threads(new), \n     messages(inbox), recipients. The is_member ACL gate is consulted twice over the same \n     store rows (write-side admission + read-side query), never on the wire. Full doc at \n     docs/fabric-architecture.md (also published as \n     naddr1qq08getwv4uz6etyvajj6enpvfexjcedv9exx6rfw3jkxar4wfjszrthwden5te0dehhxtnvdakqygqf6j \n     9p5hd7zdqy5u5kxncadwnj94q9zdrgm4cner4r3j5m0dhjcupsgqqqw4rsnqjhdr). Where is this wrong \n     or under-thought? Especially keen on: (a) thread keying across fabrics, (b) optimistic \n     vs echo write-reflection, (c) whether the Provider/store seam is the right cut. \n " -- no session id to know who it came from \n  \n Assistant: Real gap — the injected mention names the agent (`claude@tenex-edge`) but not the **session** it came from, so the recipient can't reply to the right sibling session. Let me find where that injection string is built. [...] ## What I found \n  \n 1. **The current entity table** (`inbox` row) listed `from_pubkey` (autho