d208c-3 | 2026-06-17T23:56:25Z | session:d208c058-7b2b-4ff8-bb82-d63623d51097 | ## What an injected mention looks like now \n  \n Before: `[mention from claude@tenex-edge] <body>` \n After: `[mention from claude@tenex-edge · reply-to 019eac61] <body>` \n  \n `reply-to <handle>` is the literal value to pass to `tenex-edge send-message --recipient <handle>`. \n  \n ## The end-to-end thread (6 files) \n  \n - **`domain.rs`** — `Mention.from_session: Option<String>`. \n - **`codec/kind1.rs`** — encodes a `["from-session", id]` wire tag and decodes it back; header table + a new test (`mention_emits_from_session_tag_and_back_compat_decodes_none`) proving emit/decode and that an old-peer event without the tag decodes to `None`. \n - **`state.rs`** — `InboxRow.from_session`; `from_session` column added in **both** the `SCHEMA` const (for tests) **and** an `ALTER TABLE` migration (for existing `state.db`); `enqueue_mention` + both `SELECT`s carry it. The inbox PK `(mention_event_id, target_session)` is untouched, so the session-targeted dedup-bypass idempotency is preserved. \n - **`runtime.rs`** — the `Mention → InboxRow` materialization copies `from_session`. \n - **`server.rs`** — the send path stamps `from_session: Some(rec.session_id)`; `rows_to_json` now emits `from_session` + a computed `reply_to`. \n - **`cli.rs`** — two shared helpers (`mention_reply_handle`, `format_mention_line`) replace all **five** duplicated format sites (inbox, wait-for-mention, turn-start injection, turn-check injection, daemon JSON), so the format is defined once. \n  \n **The reply handle is precise but safe**: it uses the sender's exact session id *only when that session resolves on the recipient's side*; otherwise it falls back to `slug@project`, which always routes to the agent. So it's actionable whether or not session-precision is available.
d208c-4 | 2026-06-17T23:56:25Z | session:d208c058-7b2b-4ff8-bb82-d63623d51097 | **1. Cut the seam along concerns, not kinds.** The `Codec` trait today fuses wire-mapping + subscription model + ACL (NIP-29 group management baked into `kind1`). The proposal replaces it with a **`FabricProvider`** that bundles four single-responsibility capabilities: \n  \n | Capability | Owns | \n |---|---| \n | **Lifecycle reactor** | side-effects of `ProjectOpened` etc. — nip29 creates a group, mls invites, kind1 no-ops | \n | **Membership source** | hydrates & streams the ACL from its native source | \n | **Wire codec** | pure `DomainEvent ⇄ envelope` | \n | **Delivery** | publish + subscribe-for-scope; owns REQ-filters / gossip / MLS-stream *privately* | \n  \n The `filters → Vec<Filter>` relay-REQ shape stops being on the public seam, so a push/MLS delivery model becomes expressible. \n  [...] The fix is to push the boundary up to the types that are already abstract. Instead of codec-speaks-nostr + transport-plumbs-nostr (both nostr-typed), make the **transport** the seam and let it own the entire wire mapping internally: \n  \n ```rust \n trait Fabric { \n     async fn publish(&self, ev: &DomainEvent, as_agent: &Identity) -> Result<()>; \n     fn subscribe(&self, scope: &SubScope) -> impl Stream<Item = DomainEvent>; \n } \n ``` \n  \n Now `encode`/`decode`/`filters`/`EventBuilder` all become private implementation details of a `NostrFabric`. NIP-29 vs. open-relay becomes a *config of that fabric*, not a different `Codec`. And a non-nostr transport (MLS-native, gRPC) is a sibling `impl Fabric`, not an impossible-to-write `Codec`. \n  \n **The current design's actual claim** is narrower than the prose suggests: *"swap one Nostr NIP layout for another without touching domain."* That it delivers cleanly. *"Swap Nostr for a different protocol"* — it does not, because the seam traffics in `nostr_sdk` types. Whether that's a real problem depends on whether you ever intend to leave nostr. If every plausible future (NMP, Marmot) is nostr-shaped, the current seam is correctly priced and lifting it to `DomainEvent`/`SubScope` is over-abstraction. If you genuinely want MLS-native or non-relay transports on the table, the seam is one level too low and `filters` in particular won't survive the move.
