d208c-11 | 2026-06-17T23:56:25Z | session:d208c058-7b2b-4ff8-bb82-d63623d51097 |  \n | Fabric | project *list* source | *description* source | authority / consistency | \n |--------|----------------------|---------------------|------------------------| \n | **nip29** | groups the agent belongs to (reverse of `39002`) / relay group enumeration | relay-authored `kind:39000` group metadata | **canonical & shared** — one source, all machines agree | \n | **mls** | MLS groups in local state | group-context extension / a metadata message | **member-authored**, cryptographically scoped to the group | \n | **kind1** | *derived*: observed `t`-tags + local list of dirs you've run in | **none native** → local descriptor file or a self-published note | **client-local** — two machines can disagree; eventually-divergent | \n  \n The sharp edge is kind1: groups are just `t`-tags, so there is **no native carrier for a description and no authoritative project registry**. The domain must therefore tolerate `description: Option<String>` and accept that for some fabrics the list is *derived/observed* rather than *enumerated*, and metadata is local-only. That's the same class of concession as kind1's client-side membership enforcement — it's not a flaw in the abstraction, it's the abstraction correctly surfacing that the fabric has no shared truth here. \n  [...] Assistant: Mostly yes — agent *enumeration* fits the pattern exactly. But agent *metadata* has one real asymmetry from project metadata that's worth being precise about, because it's load-bearing. \n  \n ## Agent list — same pattern \n  \n `list_agents()` is another `(query, stream)` view off the **State-source** capability, with the same per-fabric source variation and the same kind1 concession: \n  \n | Fabric | agent-list source | scope | \n |--------|-------------------|-------| \n | nip29 | members of the group(s) you're in (reverse of `39002`) → pubkeys | per-group | \n | mls | the MLS group roster keys | per-group | \n |