rollo-26 | 2026-06-18T00:59:27Z | session:rollout-2026-06-09T15-35-48-019eac61-c1bb-7391-b237-7378101f099a |     for tenex-edge. Core thesis: a CQRS split where (1) ALL reads come from one unified \n     local store (state.db), and (2) a 'Fabric Provider' (kind1/nip29/mls/a2a) is a write- \n     side materializer that decodes -> ACL-admits -> derives -> upserts canonical rows; how \n     data is hydrated is invisible to readers. Provider bundles 4 SRP capabilities: \n     Lifecycle, Materializer (composes Wire-codec + Delivery), Wire-codec, Delivery. \n     Entities: projects+meta, agents+identity, membership, presence/status, threads(new), \n     messages(inbox), recipients. The is_member ACL gate is consulted twice over the same \n     store rows (write-side admission + read-side query), never on the wire. Full doc at [...] Assistant: TLDR: tenex-edge becomes a **local fabric daemon with a unified read model**. \n  \n Every host adapter, Claude, Codex, opencode, future apps, stays thin. They say: “open this project”, “send this message”, “what’s in my inbox?”, “who’s here?” They do not know Nostr kinds, NIP-29 groups, MLS, tags, relays, or codecs. \n  \n The daemon owns `state.db` and the fabric connection. All reads come from `state.db`: projects, agents, membership, presence/status, threads, messages, recipients. That store is the product contract. \n  \n The fabric provider is only on the write/materialization side. A provider, `kind1`, `nip29`, `mls`, `a2a`, owns lifecycle, delivery, wire encoding, and materialization. It receives raw fabric events, decodes them, verifies identity, checks ACL membership, derives canonical rows, and writes them into the store.
