ses_1-22 | 2026-06-18T01:20:55Z | session:ses_1308a0757ffe8RvTvZs19Cq60r | Incoming messages are handled two ways: \n  \n 1. **`tenex-edge wait-for-mention`** — blocks until a mention arrives, then prints it and exits. Designed to run in the background; the agent harness wakes up when it exits. \n 2. **`tenex-edge inbox`** — reads + drains pending mentions (used by opencode's `hook --type user-prompt-submit` path). \n  \n So `tmux` is for control-plane ops (spawn, attach, status), while message listening is via `wait-for-mention` or `inbox`. [...] Assistant: After reading the code, I was wrong. `tenex-edge tmux` does handle incoming messages indirectly: \n  \n The **daemon** calls `ring_doorbells()` (`src/tmux.rs:444`) after every mention notification. This finds sessions with unread inbox that have a live tmux endpoint, and injects the doorbell text ("You have new tenex-edge mentions. Run `tenex-edge inbox` to read and reply.") directly into their tmux pane via `send-keys`. \n  \n So the tmux system **does** deliver incoming messages — not by listening, but by the daemon actively injecting a doorbell nudge into idle tmux panes whenever a mention arrives. The agent then reads it and runs `tenex-edge inbox`. \n  \n The TUI itself (`tmux_tui`) is for browsing/attaching/spawning/resuming sessions, not for message listening.
